! Graphs of Transformations of Sine and Cosine
We now consider graphs of functions that are transformations of the sine and cosine func-
tions. Thus, the graphing techniques of Section 2.5 are very useful here. The graphs we
obtain are important for understanding applications to physical situations such as har-
monic motion (see Section 5.6), but some of them are beautiful graphs that are interest-
ing in their own right.
It's traditional to use the letter x to denote the variable in the domain of a function. So
from here on we use the letter x and write y " sin x, y " cos x, y " tan x, and so on to
denote these functions.
E X A M P L E  1 Cosine Curves
Sketch the graph of each function.
(a) f 1x 2 " 2 ! cos x (b) g1x 2 " #cos x
